message.content: We start by rationalizing the denominator. Multiplying the numerator and denominator by the conjugate of the denominator, $\sqrt{16}+\sqrt{2}$, gives: \begin{align*}\frac{\sqrt{32}}{\sqrt{16}-\sqrt{2}}&=\frac{\sqrt{32}(\sqrt{16}+\sqrt{2})}{(\sqrt{16}-\sqrt{2})(\sqrt{16}+\sqrt{2})}\\ &=\frac{\sqrt{32}(\sqrt{16}+\sqrt{2})}{16-2}\\ &=\frac{\sqrt{64}\sqrt{2}+\sqrt{32}\sqrt{2}}{14}\\ &=\frac{8\sqrt{2}+4\sqrt{2}}{14}\\ &=\frac{12\sqrt{2}}{14}\\ &=\frac{6\sqrt{2}}{7}\end{align*}Thus, the answer is $\frac{6\sqrt{2}}{7}$, and $A+B+C+D=6+2+0+7=\boxed{15}$.
